  "text": "The Android Activity lifecycle is implemented across multiple components in the AOSP framework:\n\n1. **Activity.java** (core/java/android/app/Activity.java, line 767): The base Activity class extends ContextThemeWrapper and defines the lifecycle callback methods (onCreate, onStart, onResume, onPause, onStop, onDestroy) at lines 1864, 2151, 2229, 2663, 2892, and 2936 respectively. These protected methods are called by the framework at appropriate times during the activity's lifecycle.\n\n2. **ActivityThread.java** (core/java/android/app/ActivityThread.java, line 302): The ActivityThread class extends ClientTransactionHandler and represents the main thread of an Android application. It is responsible for processing server transactions that drive lifecycle transitions. The class imports lifecycle constants (ON_CREATE, ON_START, ON_RESUME, ON_PAUSE, ON_STOP, ON_DESTROY) from ActivityLifecycleItem and executes the appropriate lifecycle callbacks on the Activity object.\n\n3. **ActivityRecord.java** (services/core/java/com/android/server/wm/ActivityRecord.java, line 409): The ActivityRecord class extends WindowToken and represents a server-side record of an Activity. This class manages the activity's state within the window manager and tracks lifecycle transitions on the system server side.\n\n4. **ActivityTaskManagerService.java** (services/core/java/com/android/server/wm/ActivityTaskManagerService.java, line 323): The ActivityTaskManagerService class extends IActivityTaskManager.Stub and is the system service that manages activity stacks and tasks. It orchestrates the overall activity lifecycle, managing which activities are running, paused, or stopped, and initiating transitions between these states.\n\nThe lifecycle flow: When an activity is launched, ActivityTaskManagerService schedules lifecycle transitions. These are communicated to ActivityThread via client transactions. ActivityThread then processes these transactions and invokes the corresponding lifecycle callback methods on the Activity object (onCreate, onStart, onResume, etc.), while ActivityRecord maintains the server-side state of the activity."
}

